sql:
SELECT DISTINCT closure_date
FROM foia_requests
WHERE request_status = 'Closed';

SELECT case_no, date_received
FROM foia_requests
ORDER BY date_received DESC;

external_knowledge:
- FOIA (Freedom of Information Act) requests refer to formal applications made by individuals or organizations to access information held by public bodies; 
- Request duration refers to the time between the request's receipt and closure; 
- Access metrics include the count of unique documents accessed, viewed, and downloaded for each request; 
- Interaction counts are calculated by summing the view and download counts for each request; 
- Total interactions and overall request counts provide an aggregate view of request activity.

Closure impact refers to the effect of different document types and versions on the time it takes to close FOIA requests; A higher closure impact indicates a longer time to close requests.
Document types and versions are identifiers for different types of documents; 
The rolling average of closure days is a measure of the average time it takes to close requests for each document type and version, considering a moving window of data; 
The recursive increment of closure averages represents the cumulative effect of document types and versions on the closure of requests.

